        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Validation activities must use the same or geometrically similar device and span the COU operating envelope. Fluid properties must match the intended use conditions within documented tolerances. Gradation 3 requires explicit mapping between validation scenario and COU scenario."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error as a distinct credibility factor addresses iterative convergence residuals and floating-point arithmetic errors in custom or in-house solver implementations where the solver internals are accessible for audit. In this assessment, the commercial solver ANSYS Fluent 2023R2 is used under a vendor-validated QMS (covered under the Software Quality Assurance factor). Iterative convergence is monitored via residual drop to 1×10⁻⁶ for all equations and confirmed by QoI stabilisation over the final 500 iterations; no separate solver-error audit of internal floating-point operations is possible or required for a commercial code assessed under SQA. The factor is therefore not applicable to this COU and solver configuration; its substantive content is fully subsumed by the Software Quality Assurance and Numerical Code Verification factors assessed above."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Use error as a credibility factor addresses the risk that an analyst incorrectly configures or applies the model in a manner inconsistent with its validated scope — a concern primarily relevant when the model is deployed by end-users who are not the original developers (e.g., a regulatory submission tool distributed to multiple sites). In this COU, the CFD model is developed, validated, and applied exclusively by the same qualified engineering team under the same QMS that governs the SQA factor. All simulation runs are executed by analysts who participated in the validation study, using locked simulation templates with version-controlled input decks. There is no transfer of the model to a separate user population, and no self-service or automated deployment pathway exists. The conditions that make use error a meaningful credibility concern are therefore absent, and the factor is not applicable to this specific deployment context."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "The k-ω SST turbulence model is selected based on published benchmark comparisons for confined rotating flows. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model is the FDA-recommended formulation. Model form uncertainty is bounded by the validation comparison error (8.3 % mean NIH error). Gradation 3 requires documented justification of model form selection; this is provided in the modelling assumptions report.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/model-form",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Turbulence and hemolysis sub-model selections must be justified against published benchmarks for similar flow configurations. Model form uncertainty contribution must be estimated and shown to be within acceptable bounds relative to the total uncertainty budget. Gradation 3 requires a documented modelling assumptions report."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "All boundary conditions (inlet velocity profiles, outlet pressure, wall roughness, rotational speed) are derived from calibrated measurements with documented uncertainty. Material properties (viscosity, density, RBC fragility parameters) are sourced from peer-reviewed literature with uncertainty ranges used as Monte Carlo input distributions. Input uncertainty propagation is complete.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/model-inputs",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "All model inputs must be traceable to calibrated measurements or peer-reviewed property data. Uncertainty ranges must be assigned to each input and propagated through the model. Gradation 3 requires a complete input uncertainty register with source citations."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Experimental hemolysis measurements obtained from three independent test runs at each of the five operating points (15 total runs). Repeatability assessed; coefficient of variation below 8 % across runs. Sample size and repeatability are consistent with Gradation 2 requirements for MRL 5 validation at this stage of development.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/test-samples",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Minimum three independent experimental replicates per operating point. Coefficient of variation across replicates must be reported. Gradation 2 requires documented repeatability assessment; Gradation 3 would additionally require inter-laboratory reproducibility data."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
